<div class="content-ad">	<div data-cb-ad-id="ad_300x250_default" class="ad-unit ad-300x250 default desktop"><div data-tags="design,led,kinetic-energy,sand,wish-you-were-here" data-post-headline="Sand Can Light Up A Room" data-post-id="503861239" data-dfp-sz="300x250" data-is-scroll-triggered="true" data-zone-class="Zone_300x" data-slot="default" data-mode="iframe" data-random="45779874" data-size="300x250" style="display: none;" class="ad-container"></div><iframe style="display: none;" height="250" width="300" allowTransparency="true" hspace="0" marginHeight="0" marginWidth="0" vspace="0" scrolling="no" frameBorder="0" class="ad-iframe-45779874-template"></iframe></div></div><p data-textannotation-id="6f54eb24b04d25889810138efabeba09">Trofe created two designs for this month's Wanted Design 2013. Both are hourglasses that use the kinetic energy of falling sand to power a light bulb. One model is a sort of torch/flashlight-type situation, and the other is a flippable stool. It's a small step, but at least now you'll have enough light and a place to sit while you watch the environmental collapse of our planet. [<a href="http://inhabitat.com/nyc/danielle-trofes-led-hourglass-lamps-use-the-kinetic-power-of-sand-to-produce-light/http://inhabitat.com/nyc/danielle-trofes-led-hourglass-lamps-use-the-kinetic-power-of-sand-to-produce-light/" target="_blank">Inhabitat</a>]</p><div id="inset_groups" class="hide"></div></div></div><div class="ten mobile-four columns push-two marquee-border"><div class="row collapse"></div></div><div class="columns twelve mobile-four"><div class="post-modifiers-wrapper" data-forpost="503861239"><div class="js_message post-action-message inline mrm text-tiny proxima"></div><div class="post-modifiers inline">	<span class="js_liked-msg-place"></span><div class="button dropdown split secondary js_toolsmenu" data-usertools="true" data-repost="true"><a href="#" class="js_like has-tooltip tip-bottom" data-tooltip title="Recommend"><span class="icon notr